Why? Because if Black simply connects at A, 1 and 2 are free forcing moves for White. Similarly, if Black plays at 2, White can connect at 1 and will still have local forcing moves. If Black barbarically pushes through at 1, White can respond at 2, and Black will die in the corner -- in this line, T2 is an invaluable resource for White.]LB[pr:1][rl:3][rr:2][sq:A];W[pr];B[rl];W[rr];B[sq];W[lq]C[And now we have a giant fight in the center. Since Black gets sente, the position is slightly favorable for Black.])(;B[qn];W[pn];B[oq])(;B[rp]C[Here, White A is most active. Because that puts pressure on Black's central stones, which he can defend with B or C, then White can come back and poke at Black's corner stones with 1 or 2.

